{{italic title}} {{Infobox comic book title | title = ''The Glasgow Looking Glass'' (also known as ''The Northern Looking Glass'') | image = | image_caption = | code = | hero = | appearances = | pages = | layout = | story = | ink = | date = 11 June 1825&nbsp;– 3 April 1826 | first = | last = | url = }}
'''''The Glasgow Looking Glass''''' was the first mass-produced publication to tell stories using illustrations, and as such is regarded as the earliest comics magazine. The final issue was published on 3 April 1826.<ref>{{cite news |title=World's first comic book from Glasgow in spotlight |url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/books/world-s-first-comic-book-from-glasgow-in-spotlight-1-2974087 |first=Tristan |last=Stewart-Robertson |work=The Scotsman |date=24 June 2013 |accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref>
==Publishing history== The title was published by Glasgow [[Lithography|lithographic]] printer John Watson<ref>{{cite web|title=The Glasgow Looking Glass|url=http://special.lib.gla.ac.uk/exhibns/month/june2005.html|work=University of Glasgow|accessdate=30 May 2015}}</ref> and its principal strip illustrator was [[William Heath (artist)|William Heath]]. The fourth issue contained ''History of a Coat'', its first comic strip. After the fifth issue, the title was changed to ''The Northern Looking Glass'' to reflect broader Scottish concerns.
==Format== The fortnightly publication provided satirical snapshots of Glasgow society, British culture and Nineteenth century fashions. Innovations included use of the term "[[Cliffhanger|To be continued]]" and [[word balloons]].
